<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.zwire.com/site/news.cfm?newsid=5692576&amp;BRD=1169&amp;PAG=461&amp;dept_id=17708&amp;rfi=6">Source.</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
SARATOGA SPRINGS -- The Soviet Union and United States had a mutual understanding about the horrors of nuclear weapons, even while heading toward the brink of World War III in October 1962. <br>
In fact, the Cold War was based on a policy of nuclear deterrence.<br>
<br>
That's what distinguishes the Cuban Missile Crisis from today's threats posed by Iraq and Middle Eastern terrorist groups, a Skidmore professor said.<br>
<br>
''Kennedy and Khrushchev both realized they would lose if you went to nuclear war,'' associate history professor Jennifer Delton said. ''The Soviet Union had an empire to lose.''<br>
<br>
''These people don't have anything to lose. That's why these conflicts are much scarier.''<br>
<br>
Journalist Max Frankel, in a ''Smithsonian Magazine'' article, said there are distinct differences between Khrushchev and Osama bin Laden, architect of the Sept. 11, 2001, terrorist attacks on America.<br>
<br>
''Our Soviet foes 40 years ago -- even though we demonized them as evil aggressors -- were rational rivals who valued life,'' he said. ''We played nuclear poker against them but shared a common interest in the casino's survival.''<br>
<br>
The missile crisis started with Cuban President Fidel Castro's ascension to power in 1959 and a failed U.S. attempt to overthrow him with the Bay of Pigs Invasion in April 1961. American intelligence was aware of Soviet activity in Cuba during the summer of '62, but it wasn't until Oct. 14 that surveillance photos confirmed the presence of missile bases.<br>
<br>
Two days later, Kennedy considered an air strike to knock out bases before they could become operational. Instead, he and a team of closest advisers spent five days planning a U.S. response.<br>
<br>
''They had, it was estimated, about 10 days before the missiles would be on pads ready for firing,'' wrote Arthur M. Schlesinger Jr., Kennedy's special assistant.<br>
<br>
On Oct. 22, JFK told America about the missiles in a national television broadcast.<br>
<br>
''Kennedy becomes alarmed, decides to put a quarantine around Cuba and orders the Soviets to remove their missiles,'' Delton said. ''For about a week, there's this standoff when the world is riveted.''<br>
<br>
Finally, with the planet teetering on the precipice of nuclear destruction, a deal is struck on Sunday, Oct. 28, in which Kennedy promises not to invade Cuba in exchange for Soviet missile removal.<br>
<br>
''It was all over, and barely in time,'' Schlesinger wrote. ''If word had not come that Sunday, if work had continued on the bases, the United States would have had no real choice but to take action against Cuba the next week.''<br>
<br>
Why were missiles put in Cuba?<br>
<br>
Khrushchev said it was to prevent an American invasion. But the U.S. also held a huge nuclear advantage at the time and Soviet hard-liners were calling for a military buildup. Putting missiles 90 miles from America's doorstep would shift the balance of power, Khrushchev thought. It would also free up more money to boost the USSR's backward food and consumer industries.<br>
<br>
Khrushchev was counting on Kennedy's youth and inexperience to pull this off. It turned out to be his greatest mistake.<br>
<br>
''From the moment of challenge the American president never had a doubt about the need for a hard response,'' Schlesinger wrote. <br>
<br>
Huge headlines appeared in American newspapers saying, ''Khrushchev blinks.''<br>
<br>
To this day, debate continues about who really gave in to who, because the U.S. also agreed to remove its own Jupiter missiles from Turkey at a later date.<br>
<br>
''Kennedy said, 'I don't want to appear that I'm caving in to the Soviet Union,''' Delton said.<br>
<br>
''As more has been revealed, it becomes very clear that things could have escalated into nuclear warfare,'' she said. ''I think the people in Kennedy's small group of advisers were really shaken up by this.''<br>
<br>
Forty years ago, communication between the Kremlin and White House was almost primitive. The crisis led to the installation of a ''hot line'' aimed at averting similar future incidents.<br>
<br>
Delton said Castro felt somewhat betrayed by the Soviets, because he wasn't included in negotiations between the two superpowers.<br>
<br>
''He feels like he was used as a pawn and the Soviet Union is not a reliable ally,'' she said. ''The one thing Castro really wanted were the missiles.''<br>
<br>
Kennedy had suffered a loss of reputation from the Bay of Pigs and construction of the Berlin Wall. Resolving the missile crisis peacefully, while making the Soviets back down, was his finest hour without doubt.<br>
<br>
''Throughout the crisis, he coolly and exactly measured the level of force necessary to deal with the level of threat,'' Schlesinger wrote. ''At every stage, he gave his adversary time for reflection and reappraisal, taking care not to force him into 'spasm' reactions or to cut off his retreat.''<br>
<br>
''It was this combination of toughness and restraint of will, nerve and wisdom, so brilliantly controlled, so matchlessly calibrated, that dazzled the world.''<br>
<br>
Sources: October 2002 ''Smithsonian Magazine'' -- ''Learning from the Missile Crisis,'' by Max Frankel. ''A Thousand Days: John F. Kennedy in the White House,'' by Arthur M. Schlesinger Jr. <br>
